Identification of Predictor Variables using Statistical Tests

Correlation analysis for numerical features

In[]:
# Define predictor variables
predictor_from_corr = []
numerical_cols = ['months_loan_duration', 'amount', 'percent_of_income', 'years_at_residence', 'age', 'existing_loans_count', 'dependents', 'default']
# Correlation Analysis
correlation = dataset[numerical_cols].corrwith(dataset['default']).abs().sort_values(ascending=False)
predictor_from_corr.extend(correlation.index[1:4])  # Choose top 3 numerical features with highest absolute correlation

for feature in predictor_from_corr:
    correlation_value = dataset[feature].corr(dataset['default'])
    print(f"{feature} is correlated with default | Correlation: {correlation_value:.4f}")
print('Predictor variables from correlation analysis:', predictor_from_corr) # Print the predictor variables identified from correlation analysis

predictor_from_corr.extend(predictor_from_corr)

ANOVA F-test for numerical features

In[]:
# ANOVA F-test (for numerical features)
predictors_anova = []
for feature in numerical_columns:
    f_statistic, p_value = f_oneway(dataset[dataset['default'] == 1][feature], dataset[dataset['default'] == 0][feature])
    if p_value < 0.05:
        predictors_anova.append(feature)
        print(f"{feature} is correlated with default | P-Value: {p_value}")

# Print predictor variables
print("Predictor Variables from Anova F-test:", predictors_anova)

months_loan_duration is correlated with default | P-Value: 6.488049877187189e-12
amount is correlated with default | P-Value: 8.797572373533373e-07
percent_of_income is correlated with default | P-Value: 0.022035486306960176
age is correlated with default | P-Value: 0.003925339398278295
Predictor Variables from Anova F-test: ['months_loan_duration', 'amount', 'percent_of_income', 'age']

among all the predictor variables resulted from Anova test 'percent_of_income' is having a greater p-value i.e. 0.022035486306960176.Also 'percent_of_income' is not resulted from correlation test as a predictor. Taking these observations into account a finalised predictor list from numerical features would be

numerical_predictors = ['months_loan_duration', 'amount', 'age']

Chi-Square test for categorical features

In[]:
# Chi-Square Test
predictors_chi_square = []
categorical_columns = ['checking_balance', 'credit_history', 'purpose', 'savings_balance', 'employment_duration', 'other_credit', 'housing', 'job', 'phone']
for feature in categorical_columns:
    contingency_table = pd.crosstab(dataset[feature], dataset['default'])
    _, p_value, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
    if p_value < 0.05:
        predictors_chi_square.append(feature)
        print(f"{feature} is correlated with default | P-Value: {p_value}")

print('Categorical predictors:', predictors_chi_square)

checking_balance is correlated with default | P-Value: 1.2189020722893845e-26
credit_history is correlated with default | P-Value: 1.2791872956750918e-12
savings_balance is correlated with default | P-Value: 2.761214238568249e-07
employment_duration is correlated with default | P-Value: 0.0010454523491402541
other_credit is correlated with default | P-Value: 0.0016293178186473534
housing is correlated with default | P-Value: 0.00011167465374597664
Categorical predictors: ['checking_balance', 'credit_history', 'savings_balance', 'employment_duration', 'other_credit', 'housing']

  • Columns 'amount', 'age', and 'months_loan_duration' contains non-null numerical data so no pre-processing is needed.whereas all the other columns has categorical data which needs encoding it into numerical values.

  • Column 'employment_duration' seems to have ordinal properties since the categories represent different durations of employment, which have a natural order.

       *   'employment_duration' column needs to be encoded into numerical values, preserving the ordinal relationship.
   *    For ordinal encoding,categories can be mapped to numerical values based on their order.
   *   'unemployed': 1,
       '< 1 year': 2   
       '1 - 4 years': 3  
       '4 - 7 years': 4  
       '> 7 years': 5

  • For the remaining categorical columns one-hot encoding can be utilised to convert to numeric values.

      *   To achieve this, get_dummies() function from pandas library is to be used. This method allows us to express each category in a column as a binary feature. This procedure generates new binary columns for each of the original categorical columns.
  *   By doing so, we ensure that the categorical data is in a format suitable for machine learning algorithms without establishing any ordinal link between the categories.
In[]:
# Define the mapping for ordinal encoding
employment_duration_mapping = {
    'unemployed': 1,
    '< 1 year': 2,
    '1 - 4 years': 3,
    '4 - 7 years': 4,
    '> 7 years': 5
}

# Apply ordinal encoding to the 'employment_duration' column
model_data['employment_duration'] = model_data['employment_duration'].map(employment_duration_mapping)

Data Preparation: Splitting into Training and Testing Sets

In[]:
# Define predictors and target variable
X = ML_data.drop('default', axis=1)
y = ML_data['default']

Standerdization or Normalization?. what to choose?

Predictors and target variables are all set. But before proceeding with splitting the data into training and testing sets it's best to standertize or normalize the numerical data depending on the nature of data to ensure that all features have the same scale, making the algorithm work effectively.

In[]:
# Let's observe whether the data is guassian distributed

# Plot the distribution
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 20))
for i, col in enumerate(Final_predictors):
    plt.subplot(3, 3, i+1)
    sns.histplot(model_data[col], kde=True)
    plt.title(col)
    plt.xlabel('')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

A wave pattern is seen in the histograms, it indicates that data does not follow a guassian distribution.

Given this observation, normalization (MinMaxScaler) would be more appropriate for this dataset, as it does not assume any specific distribution of the data.

In[]:

Model Training and Evaluation

  • Depending on the nature of the data, size of the dataset and the characteristics of data, a model should be choosen.

  • "Predicting whether a customer will default or not" is a classification problem. For classification problems like these , Following models can be used.

        *  Logistic Regression
    *  Decision Trees
    *  Random Forest
    *  Support Vector Machines (SVM)
    *  Gradient Boosting Machines (e.g., XGBoost, LightGBM, CatBoost)

Logistic Regression

In[]:
# Initialize the Logistic Regression model
model = LogisticRegression()

# Train the model
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Make predictions on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Evaluate the model
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
print("Accuracy:", accuracy)
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))
print("\nConfusion Matrix:\n", confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred))

Observations:

Accuracy The Logistic Regression model has an accuracy of about 0.755, which means it properly predicts customers' default statuses 75.5% of the time.

Precision:
Precision for class 0 (non-defaulters) is 0.78, indicating that 78% of customers predicted as non-defaulters are indeed non-defaulters. The precision for class 1 (defaulters) is 0.63, indicating that 63% of the customers projected as defaulters are in fact defaulters. Class 0 has a recall of 0.90, indicating that 90% of non-defaulters are properly anticipated.

Recall:
Class 0 has a recall of 0.90, indicating that 90% of non-defaulters are properly anticipated. The recall for class 1 is 0.41, which means that 41% of the actual defaulters were properly predicted as defaulters.

F1-score:
The F1-score represents the harmonic mean of precision and recall. It strikes a balance between precision and recall.

Overall, the model appears to perform pretty well. However, given the class imbalance (more non-defaulters than defaulters),other evaluation measures like the ROC-AUC score or the precision-recall curve must be looked at.

In[]:
# Plot ROC curve
fpr, tpr, thresholds = roc_curve(y_test, model.predict_proba(X_test)[:, 1])
roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

# Plot feature importance
coef = model.coef_[0]
feature_importance = pd.Series(coef, index=X.columns)

feature_importance_abs.sort_values(ascending=True, inplace=True)  # Sort the absolute feature importance values
feature_importance_abs.plot(kind='barh', figsize=(10, 6))  # Use barh for horizontal bar plot
plt.title('Feature Importance')
plt.xlabel('Coefficient')
plt.ylabel('Features')
plt.xticks(np.arange(0, max(feature_importance_abs) + 0.2, 0.2))  # Set custom ticks on the x-axis
plt.show()

Observations

  1. A rough ROC curve suggests that the model's performance may not be optimal. A curve that is mainly above the diagonal line (the line that passes through the origin) indicates that the model outperforms random, but it may not distinguish well between the positive and negative categories.To improve the ROC curve, different algorithms can be given a try.
  2. precision-recall curve begins at (0, 1) and declines to (0, 0) before growing and becoming rough indicates that the model initially predicts all instances as positive, resulting in perfect recall but not so good accuracy. This behavior occurs when the model is too optimistic and forecasts everything as positive.

Observations

  1. A smooth ROC curve with minimal rigidity that extends far above the line passing through the origin is typically indicative of high model performance. It signifies that the model may attain high True Positive Rates (Sensitivity) while retaining low False Positive Rates (1 - Specificity) across a range of threshold values.

  2. However, the ROC curve goes too much above the diagonal line, it might indicate overfitting. overfitting should be checked by evaluating the model on the test set and comparing the ROC curve of the train and test sets.

  3. In precision-recall curve, at recall 0.6, the precision is 0.5, and at recall 1, the precision drops to 0.3. This indicates that as the recall increases, the precision of the model drops. It means that the model is making more false positive predictions as it tries to capture more positive cases. This can also be confirmed from FP value of 11 from confusion matrix.

  4. the features "amount", "age", "months_loan_duration", "employment_duration", and "checking_balance_unknown" have higher feature importance values. This suggests that these features are more important in predicting the target variable compared to other features.

In[]:
# Calculate ROC curve for train set
fpr_train, tpr_train, _ = roc_curve(y_train, RF_model.predict_proba(X_train)[:,1])
roc_auc_train = auc(fpr_train, tpr_train)

# Plot ROC curve for train set
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(fpr_train, tpr_train, color='blue', lw=2, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc_train)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='red', linestyle='--')
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve (Train)')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

# Plot ROC curve for test set
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='blue', lw=2, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='red', linestyle='--')
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver Operating Characteristic (ROC) Curve (Test)')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

the ROC curve for the training set is a step function and remains constant at 1, it means that the model has perfectly fit the training data, which is often an indication of overfitting. On the other hand, if the ROC curve for the test set is smooth, less rigid, and goes above the line passing through the origin, it indicates good model performance on unseen data.

Accuracy:
The accuracy of the model is 0.765, indicating that it correctly predicts the target variable around 76.5% of the time.

Precision and Recall:
Precision for class 0 (non-default) is 0.79, and for class 1 (default) is 0.67. This means that when the model predicts a non-default, it is correct 79% of the time, and when it predicts a default, it is correct 67% of the time.

Recall for class 0 is 0.91, and for class 1 is 0.41. This indicates that the model correctly identifies 91% of the non-default cases but only 41% of the default cases.

F1-score:
The F1-score for class 0 is 0.85, and for class 1 is 0.51. The F1-score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall. It is a measure of a test's accuracy and is used to balance precision and recall.

The model shows decent performance, with good accuracy, precision, and recall for the majority class (non-default). However, precision and recall for the minority class (default) are relatively lower.

Confusion matrix:
In the confusion matrix, we see that out of 141 non-defaulters, 129 were correctly classified, while out of 59 defaulters, only 24 were correctly classified.

This behavior indicates that the model has a high true positive rate while maintaining a low false positive rate at various threshold levels.
